Relative vs Absolute Referencing

Relative Referencing

Relative references automatically change when formulas are copied across rows.

Example:

=Sale_Price - Store_Cost

This was used to calculate profits for multiple sales transactions automatically.

Absolute Referencing

Absolute references keep specific cells fixed during formula copying.

Example:

=$F$2 - E2

The `$` symbol prevents Excel from changing the referenced cell while copying formulas.

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Formulas Used

Profit Formula

=Sale_Price - Store_Cost

Used to calculate profit earned on each product sale.

Commission Formula

=IF(Sale_Price > 50, 0.2 * Profit, 0.1 * Profit)

Used to calculate:
• 20% commission for products above Rs 50
• 10% commission for products below Rs 50

IF Formula

=IF(Sale_Price > 50, High_Commission, Low_Commission)

Used for commission decision-making logic.

SUM Formula

=SUM(Sale_Price_Range)

Used to calculate total sales revenue.

Pivot Table Aggregation

Used to summarize:
• Total sales by employee
• Overall business revenue

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

Pivot Table Analysis

The project includes a Pivot Table summary sheet that analyzes:

• Total sales by employee
• Overall revenue generated
• Employee performance comparison

Example Insights:
• Barns generated high total sales
• Smith had one of the largest overall revenues
• Total sales exceeded Rs 17,000

